LUMPY SKIN DISEASE - ASIA (04): TAIWAN (NEW TAIPEI) CATTLE, OIE
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this posting:
[1] Media report
[2] OIE - immediate notification

******
[1] Media report
Date: Fri 16 Apr 2021
Source: Taiwan News [edited]
https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/4178666


Beef cattle infected with lumpy skin disease (LSD) were found on a farm in New Taipei's Linkou District on Thursday (15 Apr 2021), the 1st time in Taiwan proper, according to the Council of Agriculture (COA).

Eight of 130 cows raised on the farm were discovered to have fever and nodules on their skin by New Taipei animal protection personnel during an inspection conducted on the farm the previous day [Wed 14 Apr 2021].

PCR tests by the COA's Animal Health Research Institute using blood samples taken from 3 of the 8 cows showed that they had contracted the disease caused by a capripox virus. The 8 cows were culled, cremated, and buried on the spot, with restrictions imposed on movements near the farm.

Lumpy skin disease is an infectious, eruptive, fatal [see comment] disease of cattle characterized by nodules on the skin and other parts of the body. Secondary bacterial infection often aggravates the condition.

On Thursday [15 Apr 2021] afternoon, genome sequencing conducted by the institute determined that the virus present in the Linkou cow blood is a 100% match for that found in cows on the outlying island of Kinmen in 2020 and a similar case in China in 2019.

Taiwan will report the case and related test results to the World Organisation for Animal Health.

Later Thursday [15 Apr 2021], COA Minister Chen Chi-chung said the virus could have spread from Kinmen or China to Taiwan proper.

In a bid to prevent the transmission of the disease, which does even greater harm to dairy cattle, all cattle in New Taipei will be vaccinated on Friday [16 Apr 2021], and those in other areas north of Miaoli County will be vaccinated within 3 days, ahead of those in other parts of the country, he said.

Taiwan has about 35 000 beef cows on 1197 farms nationwide with a production value of TWD 2.5 billion (USD 88.21 million) annually, according to Chen.

Meanwhile, there are 120 000 dairy cattle on 560 farms across the country, with a yearly production value of TWD 11.5 billion [USD 406 million], he said.

